%N A396357 a(1) = 2; for n > 1, a(n) is the smallest unused number placed on a hexagon spiral that has a common factor with any earlier term that is adjacent to it on the spiral.
%C A396357 A variation of A396013 and A397219 on a hexagonal spiral.
%C A396357 It is conjectured that every number greater than 1 appears.
%H A396357 Scott R. Shannon, <a href="/A396357/b396357.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..20000</a>
%H A396357 Scott R. Shannon, <a href="/A396357/a396357.png">Image of the first 1000 terms on the hexagonal spiral</a>. The number colors are graduated across the spectrum, from red to violet, to show their relative size. Small grey lines show the direction of the spiral.
%H A396357 Scott R. Shannon, <a href="/A396357/a396357_1.png">Image of the first 50000 terms on the hexagonal spiral showing their relative size</a>. Even terms are also surrounded with a white border.
%e A396357 The spiral begins:
